  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum income for Hungary's White Card?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The minimum income requirement is €3,000/month net, increased from €2,000 in 2024. You must show 6 months of bank statements demonstrating this income level, plus at least €10,000 in savings at the time of application.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Does Hungary's White Card lead to permanent residency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. The White Card is explicitly temporary—maximum 2 years (1 year + 1 renewal). After 2 years, you must leave Hungary for at least 6 months before reapplying. If you want a path to EU permanent residency, consider Portugal, Spain, or Germany instead.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family join me on the White Card?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No family reunification is available with the White Card. Your spouse and children cannot join you on dependent visas. Each family member who wants to live in Hungary must independently qualify for their own White Card with €3,000/month income.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to apostille my documents?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Hungary's White Card has simplified documentation requirements—no apostilles, no notarization, no translations required (English is accepted), and no criminal record certificate needed. This is one of the most streamlined EU digital nomad visa processes.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What tax rate will I pay in Hungary?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If you become a tax resident (183+ days in Hungary), you pay 15% flat income tax on worldwide income. Some sources suggest digital nomads may have exemptions—consult a Hungarian tax advisor to understand your specific situation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What currency does Hungary use?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Hungary uses the Hungarian Forint (HUF), not the Euro. While businesses in tourist areas may accept Euros, daily transactions are in HUF. Use a multi-currency account (Wise, Revolut) for best exchange rates, and be aware that HUF fluctuates against EUR/USD.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

